  "prompt": "What integer solutions to x and y are there for 167x+113y=1?",
  "response": "To find integer solutions to the equation \\( 167x + 113y = 1 \\), we can use the Extended Euclidean Algorithm.\n\nFirst, we can apply the Euclidean algorithm to find \\( \\gcd(167, 113) \\):\n\n1. \\( 167 = 113 \\cdot 1 + 54 \\)\n2. \\( 113 = 54 \\cdot 2 + 5 \\)\n3. \\( 54 = 5 \\cdot 10 + 4 \\)\n4. \\( 5 = 4 \\cdot 1 + 1 \\)\n5. \\( 4 = 1 \\cdot 4 + 0 \\)\n\nNow, we see that \\( \\gcd(167, 113) = 1 \\), which means that integer solutions exist for \\( 167x + 113y = 1 \\).\n\nNext, we can use the steps of the Euclidean algorithm in reverse to express 1 as a combination of 167 and 113.\n\nStarting from the last non-zero remainder:\n\\[\n1 = 5 - 4 \\cdot 1\n\\]\nSubstituting \\( 4 \\) from the previous step:\n\\[\n4 = 54 - 5 \\cdot 10 \\Rightarrow 1 = 5 - (54 - 5 \\cdot 10) = 11 \\cdot 5 - 54\n\\]\nSubstituting \\( 5 \\):\n\\[\n5 = 113 - 54 \\cdot 2 \\Rightarrow 1 = 11(113 - 54 \\cdot 2) - 54 = 11 \\cdot 113 - 22 \\cdot 54 - 54 = 11 \\cdot 113 - 23 \\cdot 54\n\\]\nSubstituting \\( 54 \\):\n\\[\n54 = 167 - 113 \\cdot 1 \\Rightarrow 1 = 11 \\cdot 113 - 23(167 - 113) = 11 \\cdot 113 - 23 \\cdot 167 + 23 \\cdot 113 = 34 \\cdot 113 - 23 \\cdot 167\n\\]\n\nTherefore, one particular solution is:\n\\[\nx = -23, \\quad y = 34\n\\]\n\nNow we can generate the general solution using the formula:\n\\[\nx = -23 + 113k\n\\]\n\\[\ny = 34 - 167k\n\\]\nfor any integer \\( k \\).\n\nSo the integer solutions \\( (x, y) \\) to the equation \\( 167x + 113y = 1 \\) are given by:\n\\[\n(x, y) = (-23 + 113k, 34 - 167k) \\quad \\text{for } k \\in \\mathbb{Z}.\n\\]",
